  "response": "The `crimes scan` finding for `src/assets/check-icon.png` is `crime_00025` (\"Icon-Sized Raster\"), and its evidence reads verbatim:\n\n- **\"dimensions: 32 × 32 px (≤ 64 threshold both sides)\"**\n- **\"format: png\"**\n- **\"consider replacing with an SVG icon — same render at every DPI, smaller bytes\"**\n\nAt those dimensions a new PNG indicator inherits the same problems the scanner is flagging on `check-icon.png`: 32×32 is below the 64px threshold on both sides, which means the asset is locked to a single resolution. On a Retina or 3× display the browser has to upscale those 32 pixels, producing soft or aliased edges, and the only way to cover other DPIs is to ship `@2x`/`@3x` variants — more files, more bytes, more drift between them. An SVG indicator, by contrast, is a handful of vector paths that render crisply at every DPI from one file, typically weighs less than a 32×32 PNG (and far less than its Retina siblings combined), and can be recolored via `currentColor` or CSS without re-exporting. For a status indicator — which is almost certainly going to sit next to text and need to adapt to theme colors — those properties matter more than they did for the original check icon, so starting from SVG avoids cementing the same \"Icon-Sized Raster\" crime into a second asset.",
